"When you can dance on nothing at all, you will never fall."
 




On Tue, Nov 16, 2010 at 1:35 AM, tim_rice09 <tim_rice09@...> wrote:
 

Coders, linguists, anyone who likes Quickscript, come one come all. I've started a project at Sourceforge called Skribanto. With a bit of work, we can have all the classics in Quickscript in a matter of days. Doing so by hand produces the best results, but takes a long time. Using precompiled phonetic dictionaries is really fast, but tends to produce really poor results. Why not use a combined approach? A full plan in available in the files section of the project, so check it out if you're interested. This will be an opensource project from the get-go and anyone that wants to help is welcome. I'm a horrible coder, but I've been using QS for over five years and actually like to proofread documents. Where are your skills?

Classic literature in Quickscript, FTW.

Skribanto link:
http://sourceforge.net/projects/skribanto/
